    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-09-09T14:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-09-09T14:29:00-05:00" n="167"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                <head>167. Circular Airgram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss>
                    to the <gloss type="to">Mission at the United Nations</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d167fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 320/9–960. Confidential. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BWB1"
                            >Buffum</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_PSEJ1">Palmer</persName>,
                        cleared by <persName corresp="#p_TNG1">Thacher</persName>, and approved and
                        signed for <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> by <persName
                            corresp="#p_WW1">Wallner</persName>. Repeated to Amman, Beirut, Baghdad,
                        Cairo, Jidda, London, Ankara, Paris, and Tel Aviv. The original number of
                        this document, <gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>–13, was changed before
                        transmission.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">CG–196</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-09-09T15:29:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 9, 1960—3:29 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Re <gloss target="#t_UNRWA1">UNRWA</gloss> item, CA–1178.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d167fn2">Circular airgram 1178, August 4, transmitted preliminary
                        views on how <gloss target="#t_UNRWA1">UNRWA</gloss> might be treated in the
                        forthcoming General Assembly session. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.,</hi>
                        320/8–460)</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Mission requested discuss with <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> at
                        earliest appropriate opportunity desirability avoidance “usual” debate
                        Palestine refugee problem 15th <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>. You
                        should, inter alia, urge <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> consider having
                        presentation <gloss target="#t_UNRWA1">UNRWA</gloss> Director’s report
                        handled in such a way as to allow item to be treated in lowest possible key,
                        e.g., circulation of report rather than oral presentation and assignment of
                        item to plenary rather than committee. (Department pleased to note that
                        nature of <persName corresp="#p_DJH1">Davis</persName>’ draft report such
                        that neither Arabs nor Israelis could take serious exception.)</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We believe acrimonious exchange between Arabs and Israelis could benefit
                        neither side and could complicate <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss>’s
                        efforts secure reasonable modus vivendi Suez transit and <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJH1">Davis</persName>’ quiet efforts rectify <gloss
                            target="#t_UNRWA1">UNRWA</gloss> relief rolls. Also, debate this year
                        might postpone and frustrate possibility of behind scenes efforts by <gloss
                            target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss> to make progress toward solution of refugee
                        problem. Key to avoidance extensive debate would seem to be persuasion of
                        Arab dels that contentious debate in 15th <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>
                        not in their interest. (We understand UK also prefers minimum <gloss
                            target="#t_UNRWA1">UNRWA</gloss> debate.)</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>We believe <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> in best position sound out
                        key Arabs, probably in first instance Jordan, <gloss target="#t_UAR1"
                            >UAR</gloss> and Saudi Arabia re informal preagreement to approve
                            <persName corresp="#p_DJH1">Davis</persName> report without partisan
                        comment. <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> will recall that res. 1456
                        (XIV) contains admirably suitable peg on which to hang avoidance <gloss
                            target="#t_UNRWA1">UNRWA</gloss> debate; it provides for review in two
                        years, i.e., at 16th <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Report <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> response foregoing suggestions.
                        Assume <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> would wish advise <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJH1">Davis</persName> of any effort avoid acrimonious
                        debate, and direct <persName corresp="#p_DJH1">Davis</persName>
                        accordingly.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
